Each carboxyl group (-COOH) in citric acid typically raises the melting point due to the ability to form strong intermolecular hydrogen bonds. Citric acid has three carboxyl groups, which would significantly increase the melting point compared to acetic acid. An alcohol group (-OH) also generally raises the melting point because of the hydrogen bonding, though not as much as the carboxyl group. Since citric acid contains an additional alcohol group, this will also contribute to increasing the melting point. Therefore, the expected increase due to the carboxyl groups would be about (3 * 45) considering each contributes roughly +45 to the melting point. The additional alcohol group could contribute about +20. So, the predicted shift from acetic acid's melting point would be (3 * 45) + 20.
